  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Establish common standards and expectations\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate on investigations\n- Share financial intelligence\n- Extradite suspects\n- Enforce cross-border legal actions\n\n3. Compliance Requirements\n- Banks required to implement anti-money laundering (AML) protocols\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- International standardization of financial oversight\n\n4. Regulatory Frameworks\n- FATF sets global standards\n- Countries adapt national laws to meet international guidelines\n- Consistent approach to detecting and preventing money laundering\n\n5. Information Sharing Mechanisms\n- Financial intelligence units (FIUs)\n- International databases\n- Real-time communication networks\n- Tracking suspicious financial activities\n\n6. Enforcement Cooperation\n- Joint investigations\n- Coordinated legal actions\n- Sanctions against non-compliant jurisdictions\n- Targeting transnational criminal networks\n\nThese intersections create a comprehensive global approach to combating money laundering.",
